Here's the complete implementation:

**Configure request size limits in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
// Configure Kestrel max request body size (must be >= your file limit)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 11 * 1024 * 1024; // 11MB to allow overhead
});
```

**Add the endpoint:**

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFile file) =>
{
    const long maxSize = 10L * 1024 * 1024;
    string[] allowedTypes = ["image/jpeg", "image/png"];

    if (file.Length == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("Empty file.");

    if (file.Length > maxSize)
        return Results.BadRequest("File exceeds 10 MB limit.");

    if (!allowedTypes.Contains(file.ContentType, StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
        return Results.BadRequest("Only JPEG and PNG files are accepted.");

    var uploadsDir = Path.Combine(app.Environment.ContentRootPath, "uploads");
    Directory.CreateDirectory(uploadsDir);

    // Prevent path traversal and collisions
    var safeFileName = $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}";
    var filePath = Path.Combine(uploadsDir, safeFileName);

    await using var stream = File.Create(filePath);
    await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

    return Results.Ok(new { fileName = safeFileName });
})
.DisableAntiforgery()          // required for API clients sending multipart/form-data
.WithRequestFormLimits(o =>    // per-endpoint form limits
{
    o.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 10L * 1024 * 1024;
});
```

**Key points:**

- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — since your pipeline calls `UseAntiforgery()`, file uploads from API clients (Postman, `fetch`, etc.) will fail without this. Remove it only if you're serving an antiforgery token to callers.
- **`WithRequestFormLimits`** — sets the multipart form limit per-endpoint so other endpoints keep the default 128 KB limit.
- **Kestrel's `MaxRequestBodySize`** — the outer ceiling; must be ≥ the form limit.
- **`Guid` filename** — prevents path traversal attacks and name collisions; the original filename is never used for storage.
